"Ward I.C.","Will global warming reduce the carbon emissions of the Yorkshire Humber Region's domestic building stock-A scoping study",2008,"Energy and Buildings","40","6",,"998","1003",,,10.1016/j.enbuild.2007.08.007,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38949188279&partnerID=40&md5=c2195c42661291dc094c128f67474145","Building Energy Analysis Unit, School of Architecture, University of Sheffield, Western Bank, Sheffield, S10 2TN, United Kingdom","Ward, I.C., Building Energy Analysis Unit, School of Architecture, University of Sheffield, Western Bank, Sheffield, S10 2TN, United Kingdom","There is evidence from the International Panel of Climate Change that the UK will experience a mean rise in ambient air temperature over the coming years. Such a rise in temperature will change the requirements for heating and cooling of domestic buildings. This scoping paper explores this issue with respect to the housing sector in the Yorkshire Humber Region of the UK and comes to the conclusion that the regions domestic sector poses major problems with respect to the stated carbon savings required by the UK Government. © 2007.","Cooling energy; Domestic energy use; Heating energy; Regional energy use","Buildings; Carbon; Cooling; Energy utilization; Global warming; Heating; Cooling energy; Domestic energy use; Heating energy; Regional energy use; Industrial emissions",,,,,,"Climate Change 2001: Synthesis Report, International Panel on Climate Change, http://www.ipcc.ch/pub/reports.htmEnergy White Paper Our energy future-creating a low carbon economy, Department for Environment Food and Rural Affairs, February 2003Climate change and the indoor environment: impacts and adaptation, TM36, Chartered Institute of Building Services Engineers, ISBN 1903287502, 2005National Energy Statistics, (2004) Monthly Statistics, , Department of Environment Transport and the Regions, National Energy Statistics; National Statistics Regional Figures for Yorkshire and the Humber, Office of